  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions around the world, including China. Money laundering involves the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The ultimate goal is to make the funds appear legitimate.\n\nIn China, the fight against money laundering is taken very seriously. The country has established stringent laws and regulations to combat this illegal activity. The **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China**, which came into effect in 2007, provides a legal framework for identifying, preventing, and prosecuting money laundering activities. Additionally, China is a member of the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, an international body that sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\nUnder Chinese law, individuals or entities found guilty of money laundering can face severe penalties, including hefty fines and imprisonment. Financial institutions are also required to implement robust anti-money laundering (AML) measures, such as customer due diligence, suspicious transaction reporting, and record-keeping.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is unequivocally prohibited by law in China, and the government is committed to enforcing these laws to maintain the integrity of the financial system.",
